1471":"1471","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1412":"1412","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1474":"1474","about 1368":"about 1368","Andover, Hampshire, England":"Andover, Hampshire, England","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Quemerford, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Calne and Quemberford, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bellett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English female personal names  <i>Belet</i>,  <i>Belot</i>, diminutives of  <i>Bel</i> (  see  Bell  ).","2  English: possibly a late variant of   Bellard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bellet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain.","French:","nickname for a handsome man, from a derivative of <i>bel</i> ‘beautiful, handsome’ (see   Bel  )."]},{"name":"Bellott","meanings":["Norman:  see  Bellett  ."]},{"name":"Bellot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Benito, Manuel, Alejandra, Felipe, Jovita, Juan, Maricela, Pedro.","Catalan: from a diminutive of <b>Belló</b> (see   Bello  ).","French: nickname from a derivative of   Bel   ‘beautiful’."]},{"name":"Bellard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Leonce, Albon, Laurent, Orelia, Vernice.","French: dissimilated form of <b>Bérard</b> (see   Berard  ).","English: apparently a derivative of Old French and Middle English <i>belle</i> + the suffix <i>-ard</i>, but the sense of <i>belle</i> is uncertain. It might be the female personal name <i>Belle</i> ‘beautiful’, the adjective <i>belle</i> ‘fine, beautiful’, or the noun <i>belle</i> ‘bell’ (see   Bell  ), in which case the surname might be synonymous with <i>beller</i> ‘bell-ringer or bell-maker’ (see   Beller  )."]},{"name":"Bell","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish (Lowlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bell</i>. As a man's name this is from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘handsome’, which was also used as a nickname. As a female name it represents a short form of   Isabel  .","English (northern) and Scottish (Lowlands): from Middle English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’ (Old English <i>belle</i>), in various applications; most probably a metonymic occupational name for a bell ringer or bell maker, or a topographic name for someone living ‘at the bell’ (as attested by 14th-century forms such as <i>John atte Belle</i>). This indicates either residence by an actual bell (e.g. a town's bell in a bell tower, centrally placed to summon meetings, sound the alarm, etc.) or ‘at the sign of the bell’, i.e. a house or inn sign (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in Scots and English).","English: from Middle English <i>bel</i> ‘fair, fine, good’ (Old French <i>bel</i> ‘beautiful, fair’). See also   Beal   1."]},{"name":"Bellotte","meanings":["Norman:  see  Bellett  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":70,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSumm